body: Can I see tests that look like the iter tests, but bounded? Just make sure they iterate over the same number of elements. I suspect it'd be an interesting comparison. Specifically, I'm looking to see what the cost of creating the iterator looks like.

Quick skim: interesting approach! Excited to dig into this. Sad to see macros. :( 

Will review monday if no one else does first.
Haha "sad to see macros" is pretty much exactly what I thought when scrolling through this.

Should we provide `RangedKeys`, `RangedValues`, `RangedValuesMut` for map, as well as ~~`RangedItems`~~ `RangedKeys` for `BTreeSet`?

> interesting approach!

Can you think of some other approach?

Unfortunately, the code is quadrupled for both ends and mut/immutable. Macros deal with the latter duplication.

I was assuming you were going to replace the Two RingBufs with two Vecs, which _should_ better optimize for the "average" case. In fact you've _kind've_ done that. Two stacks and a deque are famously "equivalent", although normally I see that used to implement a deque using two stacks, not the other way around :P

The code complexity benefits probably make it worth it, though.
Just need to fully parse the macro madness...

So I think with the exception of the match-on-a-slice in the range iterator construction, all of the macro stuff can be purged with the same Traversal/Abs tricks we already use throughout this code, right?
Ok, done review.
CC @huonw if you want to take a crack at this, too.
@pczarn Can you also add this API to BTreeSet?

This is perhaps good to go now.
- Should we provide KeyRange, ValueRange, ValueRangeMut?

> Can I see tests that look like the iter tests, but bounded?

Do you mean benchmarks?  They didn't give me meaningful results.

> Have you tried self.depth \* 2 (possibly + 1)? Since it can extend down the tree on both the left and the right, you would need to double the depth to ensure a lack of allocations.

The difference is really small. I'm not concerned about this.

> So I think with the exception of the match-on-a-slice in the range iterator construction, all of the macro stuff can be purged with the same Traversal/Abs tricks we already use throughout this code, right?

I don't think so. Traversal/Abs uses some of the macro stuff, too. There are 3 options:
- keep macros
- or expand them, adding 180 lines
- (in the future) use HKT for non-trivial parametrization over mutability
More ranges seems like overkill; hope to re-r today.

Basically r=me (feel free to squash), but this is complex enough that I'd appreciate a secondary review from @huonw or @gereeter (or anyone else, really).

Also needs another rebase :(
@Gankro, done. The comment "for ranges such as..." is irrelevant for the main example.
Needs another rebase :(
